== Overview == Kyūchū became a key concept as the counterpart to {{ill|府中|ja|府中|府中=府中|lt=Fuchū|qq=draft}} (state administration).<ref name="sekai" >[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%AE%AE%E4%B8%AD-477175 世界大百科事典 第２版「宮中」]</ref> Under a {{ill|constitutional monarchy|ja|立憲君主制|qq=draft}}, Kyūchū and Fuchū are meant to be distinct, with clear institutional responsibility for national governance. However, during the early Meiji period under the {{ill|Daijōkan system|ja|太政官制|qq=draft}}, the distinction between palace affairs and state administration was unclear. Positions such as {{ill|Daijō Daijin|ja|太政大臣|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sadaijin|ja|左大臣|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Udaijin|ja|右大臣|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sangi|ja|参議|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kyō|ja|卿|qq=draft}} were viewed as courtly roles under the emperor, rather than as independent state officials. These roles were often filled by court nobles (kuge) from traditional families, further blending the lines between courtly and governmental duties.<ref name="sekai" />
Even after the establishment of the {{ill|Meiji Constitution|ja|大日本帝国憲法|qq=draft}} and its constitutional system, the significant powers granted to the emperor allowed his close advisors within Kyūchū to wield political influence. These close associates were referred to as the "court group" or "Kyūchū group."<ref name="nipo" >[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%AE%AE%E5%BB%B7%E3%82%B0%E3%83%AB%E3%83%BC%E3%83%97-1524205 日本大百科全書(ニッポニカ)「宮廷グループ」]</ref> This group included figures such as the {{ill|Genrō|ja|元老|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal of Japan|ja|内大臣府|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Minister of the Imperial Household|ja|宮内大臣|qq=draft}}, and the {{ill|Grand Chamberlain of Japan|ja|侍従長|qq=draft}}, along with their associates. During the Shōwa period, the "old court group" was represented by {{ill|Saionji Kinmochi|ja|西園寺公望|qq=draft}}, while the "new court group" included figures such as {{ill|Fumimaro Konoe|ja|近衛文麿|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Koichi Kido|ja|木戸幸一|qq=draft}}.<ref name="nipo" />
== References == * {{ill|Tomoko Masuda|ja|増田知子|qq=draft}}, "Kyūchū," in *{{ill|Encyclopedia of Japanese History|ja|日本史大事典|qq=draft}} Vol. 2* ({{ill|Heibonsha|ja|平凡社|qq=draft}}, 1993), ISBN 978-4-582-13102-4. * {{ill|Akira Fujiwara|ja|藤原彰|qq=draft}}, "Court Group," in *{{ill|Encyclopedia of Japanese History|ja|日本歴史大事典|qq=draft}} Vol. 1* ({{ill|Shogakukan|ja|小学館|qq=draft}}, 2000), ISBN 978-4-095-23001-6. * {{ill|Seiichi Chatani|ja|茶谷誠一|qq=draft}}, *Court Influence and Politics During the Pre-War Shōwa Period* ({{ill|Yoshikawa Kobunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|qq=draft}}, 2009), ISBN 978-4-642-03792-1.
